I quoted approvingly Gibson's old 2000s dictum that Japan was further into the future than the Internet. This used to be more true than it is.

There is a curious lack of Japanese contributions in software technology. Japan has a highly educated population a good fraction of the size of US population (127m vs 300m), considerable indigenous R&D capability (albeit [declining](http://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/17/business/worldbusiness/17engineers.html?pagewanted=all)), long involvement in computing hardware, etc. Hence, if all were equal, one would expect something like a third of all major software packages written by Japanese or Internet services developed by Japanese, and so on. Instead, one notices almost a complete absence of such Japanese contributions. (To the extent one *doesn't* notice this, one is engaging in [base rate fallacy](!Wikipedia) - Japan *ought* to be producing much globally selling or popular software and its absence is surprising[^the-economist].) In software, the only major contribution I know of is the [Ruby programming language](!Wikipedia); one could argue that would-be FLOSS contributors are "bled off" or parasitized by the Anglosphere FLOSS communities (and are somehow invisible there), but I am continually struck by the almost complete absence of [FLOSS](!Wikipedia) in [doujinshi](!Wikipedia) media & the survival and massive popularity of closed-source software, where this argument should not apply. Websites are simply ugly; [Oliver Reichenstein](http://www.theverge.com/2012/7/24/3177332/ia-oliver-reichenstein-writer-interview-good-design-is-invisible "Good design is invisible: an interview with iA's Oliver Reichenstein"):

